{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514573"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12338"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.08,0.28,0.07,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110878"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4858"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93051"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1085"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41839"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110878"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of ankle pain. He thinks he might have injured it while running earlier in the week, but cannot recall any specific trauma. He has no significant medical history apart from a several day history of painful urination and frequency three weeks ago, which self-resolved. He does not take any regular medications. He does not smoke and drinks about two cans of beer a week. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 80/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.5\u00b0C. There is a right ankle effusion, and it is warmer compared to the left, with some pain and limitation of movement. The range of motion is intact. He also has some swelling of the right wrist.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cutaneous findings may be seen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psoriatic plaques","Malar rash","Erythema nodosum","Dermatitis herpetiformis","Keratoderma blennorrhagicum"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with an acute arthritis (asymmetrical joint pain without any specific trauma) after an episode of urethritis that was likely due to a sexually transmitted infection. This clinical presentation is most suggestive of reactive arthritis. Reactive arthritis is an autoimmune phenomenon, frequently associated with HLA B27 positivity, that is seen in response to certain infections. These are typically gastrointestinal or genitourinary in origin and typically involve \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003ESalmonella\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReactive arthritis is more often seen in young men. Common symptoms and signs include pain and stiffness of joints in an asymmetrical, oligoarticular pattern (most often affecting the knees); inflammatory eye disease (conjunctivitis or iritis); hyperkeratotic plaques (keratoderma blennorrhagicum); and dysuria from urethritis. Reactive arthritis occurs a few days to weeks after an infection. When caused by a sexually transmitted infection, appropriate antibiotic treatment should be administered. In Australia, mandatory reporting for contact tracing is required for sexually transmitted infections as well as some enteric infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratoderma blennorrhagicum \u003C/strong\u003E(see image below) is a characteristic skin manifestation of reactive arthritis, appearing as hyperkeratotic, waxy plaques on the palms and soles. These lesions are histologically indistinguishable from psoriasis but occur specifically in the context of reactive arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic plaques\u003C/strong\u003E are well-demarcated, erythematous plaques with silvery scale that occur in psoriasis. While psoriatic arthritis can present similarly to reactive arthritis, the preceding urethritis and acute onset make reactive arthritis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalar rash\u003C/strong\u003E is a butterfly-shaped rash across the cheeks and nose that is characteristic of systemic lupus erythematosus. This would not be expected in reactive arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema nodosum\u003C/strong\u003E presents as tender, red nodules typically on the shins and can be associated with various infections and inflammatory conditions, but is not a typical feature of reactive arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatitis herpetiformis\u003C/strong\u003E is an intensely pruritic vesicular rash associated with coeliac disease, not reactive arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reactive arthritis presents with an inflammatory arthritis, a few days to weeks after an infection, typically genitourinary or gastrointestinal.","Reactive arthritis is a disease entity in the group of seronegative spondyloarthropathies, is frequently associated with HLA B27 positivity, and can have associated inflammatory skin and ocular manifestations.","Keratoderma blennorrhagicum is a characteristic skin manifestation of reactive arthritis, appearing as hyperkeratotic plaques on palms and soles."],"references":["Cheeti A, Chakraborty RK, Ramphul K. Reactive Arthritis. [Updated 2022 Jun 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Photo Credit:Content Providers(s): CDC/ Dr. M. F. ReinTranswiki approved by: w:en:User:Dmcdevit, Public domain, via Wikimedia Commons. Available from: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Feet-Reiters_syndrome.jpg"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93051"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12338"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22005"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22005"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/QJdr6gmkOgRpkm97fqHKWaBwSvyUVS.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/QJdr6gmkOgRpkm97fqHKWaBwSvyUVS.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1008}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93051"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-05T09:07:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-05T09:09:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4858"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110878"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synony